The Office of the Public Defender in Ekiti State on Wednesday said it has mediated in over 50 marriage -related crises in the last one year. The human right protection agency lamented that marital crisis and land dispute are the two commonest societal evils affecting the peace and stability of the state. The Executive Secretary of the agency, Barrister Bolanle Wale- Awe, who made the disclosure in Ado Ekiti, on Tuesday, stated that the agency attended to a proportionate number of land dispute cases in 2019 with several similar issues are still pending before it. Wale-Awe said the government established the outfit to give free legal services, advice and mediate in marital crisis as well as land dispute, to bring justice to the doorsteps of the oppressed. According to her, “The commonest of all the issues we are handling here are cases of marital disharmony and land disputes, which bordered on fight over paternity of a child. “In many of those cases we handled, we normally conduct DNA tests and found out that most men are in the habit of denying the pregnancy they were responsible for. Some men were also fond of abandoning the upkeep of their children among other nefarious acts. “Another issue is this high tendencies of some people to fight over lands or owners of lands trying to sell a plot to two or three persons. All these are creating instability and heating up the society. “We are dealing with over 20 variant of issues to bring justice to the people and to decongest our courts, because many of the cases that will take four years in courts can be handled and settled here in a day”. The Executive Secretary who solicited for more funding for the agency to improve automation of the data processing and compilation , create conducive atmosphere for personnel said such will help in meeting other obligations that will strengthen the agency for better productivity. 